      71	/**
      72	 * Instances of this class serve as a focus point for configuration of the library's behavior and as an entry point
      73	 * to any form of code generation using the library. For this purpose, Byte Buddy offers a fluent API which allows
      74	 * for the step-wise generation of a new Java type. A type is generated either by:
      75	 * <ul>
      76	 * <li><b>Subclassing</b> some type: A subclass - as the name suggests - extends another, existing Java type. Virtual
      77	 * members of the generated type's super types can be overridden. Subclasses can also be interface extensions of one
      78	 * or several interfaces.</li>
      79	 * <li><b>Redefining</b> a type: By redefining a type, it is not only possible to override virtual methods of the
      80	 * redefined type but also to redefine existing methods. This way, it is also possible to change the behavior of
      81	 * non-virtual methods and constructors of the redefined type.</li>
      82	 * <li><b>Rebasing</b> a type: Rebasing a type works similar to creating a subclass, i.e. any method being overridden
      83	 * is still capable of invoking any original code of the rebased type. Any rebased method is however inlined into the
      84	 * rebased type and any original code is preserved automatically. This way, the type's identity does not change.</li>
      85	 * </ul>
      86	 * Byte Buddy's API does not change when a type is rebased, redefined or subclassed. All types are created via the
      87	 * {@link net.bytebuddy.dynamic.DynamicType.Builder} interface. Byte Buddy's API is expressed by fully immutable
      88	 * components and is therefore thread-safe. As a consequence, method calls must be chained for all of Byte Buddy's
      89	 * component, e.g. a method call like the following has no effect:
      90	 * <pre>
      91	 * ByteBuddy byteBuddy = new ByteBuddy();
      92	 * byteBuddy.foo()</pre>
      93	 * Instead, the following method chain is correct use of the API:
      94	 * <pre>
      95	 * ByteBuddy byteBuddy = new ByteBuddy().foo();</pre>
      96	 * <p>
      97	 * For the creation of Java agents, Byte Buddy offers a convenience API implemented by the
      98	 * {@link net.bytebuddy.agent.builder.AgentBuilder}. The API wraps a {@link ByteBuddy} instance and offers agent-specific
      99	 * configuration opportunities by integrating against the {@link java.lang.instrument.Instrumentation} API.
     100	 * </p>
     101	 *
     102	 * @see net.bytebuddy.agent.builder.AgentBuilder
     103	 */
     104	@HashCodeAndEqualsPlugin.Enhance
     105	public class ByteBuddy {
     106	
     107	    /**
     108	     * A property that controls the default naming strategy. If not set, Byte Buddy is generating
     109	     * random names for types that are not named explicitly. If set to {@code fixed}, Byte Buddy is
     110	     * setting names deterministically without any random element, or to {@code caller}, if a name
     111	     * should be fixed but contain the name of the caller class and method. If set to a numeric
     112	     * value, Byte Buddy is generating random names, using the number as a seed.
     113	     */
     114	    public static final String DEFAULT_NAMING_PROPERTY = "net.bytebuddy.naming";
     115	
     116	    /**
     117	     * The default prefix for the default {@link net.bytebuddy.NamingStrategy}.
     118	     */
     119	    private static final String BYTE_BUDDY_DEFAULT_PREFIX = "ByteBuddy";
     120	
     121	    /**
     122	     * The default suffix when defining a {@link AuxiliaryType.NamingStrategy}.
     123	     */
     124	    private static final String BYTE_BUDDY_DEFAULT_SUFFIX = "auxiliary";
     125	
     126	    /**
