 source named module while the target system loader is unnamed. It's interesting to consider if named modules can read unnamed ones. But then, it seems that a named module might not have the ability to read unnamed modules. How does this impact my understanding of module interactions?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_2tLdAMYX0bw0LFG9f28WPqZU|fc_0a4967bdb0d2adc6016a293138089c81939c41b6748f39d945", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmp=$(mktemp -d); curl -fsSL -o $tmp/byte-buddy-sources.jar https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/net/bytebuddy/byte-buddy/1.14.4/byte-buddy-1.14.4-sources.jar && unzip -p $tmp/byte-buddy-sources.jar net/bytebuddy/dynamic/loading/ClassInjector.java | grep -n \"class UsingReflection\" -A180 | sed -n '1,180p'", "timeout": 20}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 4986, "output": 1200, "cacheRead": 51712, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 57898, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781084443481, "responseId": "resp_0a4967bdb0d2adc6016a29311c72448193b0096da4e7b2166a"}}
